# Introduction

Eunoia is a Rust library for area-proportional Euler and Venn diagrams. It is
the engine behind the
[`@jolars/eunoia`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@jolars/eunoia) npm package,
the [`eunoia`](https://pypi.org/project/eunoia/) Python package, and the
[`Eunoia.jl`](https://github.com/jolars/Eunoia.jl) Julia package, as well as a
modern rewrite of the C++ backend behind the
[eulerr](https://github.com/jolars/eulerr) R package.

## Who This Is For

These docs are aimed at two audiences:

- **End users of language wrappers** (R, Python, JavaScript, Julia)
  who want to understand what the underlying library does, what its
  knobs mean, and how to read its outputs.
- **Binding authors** wiring up downstream packages. Most hosts bind
  the Rust core directly (wasm-bindgen, PyO3, extendr); native hosts
  that reach it through the C ABI have the
  [Bindings](/docs/bindings/c-abi/) section.

For Rust API reference see [docs.rs/eunoia](https://docs.rs/eunoia/);
for the TypeScript surface see the type definitions shipped with
[`@jolars/eunoia`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@jolars/eunoia).
This site is the narrative companion.

## Where to Start

- Getting started: the quickstart sections for [JavaScript](/docs/quickstart/javascript/),
  [Rust](/docs/quickstart/rust/), [Python](/docs/quickstart/python/), [R](/docs/quickstart/r/),
  or [Julia](/docs/quickstart/julia/).
- Writing a native binding via the C ABI:
  [C ABI contract](/docs/bindings/c-abi/).
- Placing labels in a downstream renderer:
  [Label placement](/docs/concepts/label-placement/) (the only fully
  written chapter so far; the rest are stubs that will fill in as
  consumers hit the gap).
